<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / BBA rises 53% to Pounds 47.4m pre-tax
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBA, the motor components group, reaped the full benefit of cost-saving
measures with a 53 per cent increase in pre-tax earnings last year, adjusted
to the new FRS 3 accounting convention.
The motors performance offset a large downturn in BBA's US-oriented aviation
parts and services operations, and virtual standstill in its industrial
division, covering industrial textiles to heavy electricals. Mr John White,
chief executive, insisted that BBA was well able to cope with an 'ominous'
downturn in the German motor industry.
BBA's group pre-tax profit of Pounds 47.4m in the year to December 31, up
from Pounds 30.9m, was earned after exceptional items and on turnover of
Pounds 1.32bn, up from 1991's Pounds 1.25bn. Profit before tax and
exceptionals was 23 per cent higher, at Pounds 60.3m (Pounds 49m). The final
dividend was held at 5.25p to make an unchanged total of 7.5p. BBA's shares
closed at 171p, up 5p.
The motor components division saw profits leap from Pounds 19.8m to Pounds
31.9m, in spite of turnover up only slightly to Pounds 621.1m from Pounds
595.7m. Mr White said the improvement reflected technical process
improvements and other cost-cutting started in 1991, particularly in
Germany.
After a record year for its German motor activities, BBA expects a 15 per
cent decline in the German original equipment market. It expects this to be
offset by business gained on several new cars, including Ford's Mondeo and
Opel's Corsa. Half BBA's motor components turnover is in the aftermarket,
for which no decline is expected.
Profits in the industrial division were virtually unchanged at Pounds 35m
(Pounds 34.9m) on sales of Pounds 486m (Pounds 458.6m). The higher aviation
turnover, up from Pounds 197.8m to Pounds 215.5m, partly reflects the merger
of BBA's Flight Services Operations with Butler Aviation International.
Sector profit slumped to Pounds 10.7m from Pounds 14.1m, as BBA steered
clear of business with carriers with potential credit worthiness problems.
With 35 per cent of total sales derived from North American operations, BBA
says it is well placed to benefit from what it sees as a strong US recovery
now under way.
However, Mr White warned of 'harsh' European economic conditions this year.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
