<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / Errors led to shortfall of Pounds 35m in business rates fund
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE DEPARTMENT of the Environment may have lost more than Pounds 35m in the
first year of collecting business rates because of errors in figures
supplied by local authorities.
The losses arose because the department accepted as reliable local authority
figures that had been qualified by their auditors.
A report published today by the National Audit Office, the government
expenditure watchdog, says the department was slow to realise the
significance of the auditors' qualifications.
Over a third of the returns sent in by local authorities had been qualified
by their auditors. The main reason was weaknesses in councils' computer
systems which made it hard to check that the correct amount of business
rates had been collected.
The returns are used to redist-ribute income from uniform bus-iness rates
between local authorities according to a nationally determined formula.
Councils that collect more than they are entitled to must pay money into a
pool; those that collect less receive a net payment.
After the end of the year, the environment department makes a final
adjustment for each council based on its audited return. Once the final
adjustment has been made, the department cannot reopen the case, even if
mistakes later emerge.
At the end of 1990-91, the first year of the system, 123 out of 366 returns
had been qualified by their auditors. The first 36 qualified returns,
covering Pounds 962m, were settled by the department without questioning the
significance of the qualifications.
Steps were taken with the remaining 87 qualified returns to resolve problems
arising from auditors' concerns. However, the audit office says there may
still have been losses where local authority computer systems provided
inadequate evidence to check the accuracy of payments.
The exact shortfall is difficult to quantify, according to the audit office.
However, it estimates that the environment department failed to collect up
to Pounds 22.5m, and wrongly paid out up to Pounds 13.2m. Some of this
shortfall may be recouped in later years, according to the audit office. The
report says that steps have been taken to improve the accuracy and
auditability of the returns for future years.
As a result of the shortfall, Sir John Bourn, head of the NAO, has qualified
his audit opinion on the environment department's 1991-92 account for
non-domestic rates.
Pooling of Non-domestic Rates and Redistribution to Local Auth-orities in
England. HC528. HMSO.
