<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / The Lex Column: Hillsdown Holdings
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Hillsdown's annual results might have dissolved the market's worst fears but
they also highlight fresh anxieties. The held dividend and the new
management's resolve to squeeze higher profits from its Pounds 4.4bn of
sales will certainly have underpinned the strong recovery in Hillsdown's
shares since September. But the yield story is rapidly exhausting itself.
Further gains will depend on strong earnings. These, though, are likely to
prove highly elusive. Under the new FRS 3 UK accounting standard, Hillsdown
recorded losses per share of 0.3p last year.
Hillsdown is wielding the butcher's knife in its attempt to improve
efficiencies. The Pounds 92.3m extraordinary reorganisation charge reflects
its serious intent to sort out 30 underperforming businesses. The
rationalisation of its poultry division shows what can be achieved.
Sterling's devaluation will also help by bolstering overseas earnings and
restoring Hillsdown's competitiveness against marauding French chickens. But
the diversity of Hillsdown's portfolio suggests surgery will be a drawn-out
process. An increasing tax charge will further hinder earnings progress this
year.
The market may also question the long term future of a low margin producer
of commodity foods. As yet, the management has scarcely addressed the
strategic issue. They are surely right to conclude that without greater
predictability of cash flow little else can follow.
</TEXT>
