<PROFILE>_AN-DCJCTAC7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930310
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In the past few years Britain, or more accurately you and I, have paid
billions of pounds replacing the rates system with the poll tax. Now we are
paying billions of pounds to replace the poll tax with the council tax
 .which looks remarkably like the rates system. Dispatches (9.00 C4) looks
at the way key decisions were taken while public attention was directed
elsewhere, and at the politicians most closely involved. Margaret Thatcher
promised in 1974 that she would abolish the rates, , but Nigel Lawson, as
Chancellor of the Exchequer, fought against the idea. It may be worth
remembering that the BBC2 drama series Mr Wroe's Virgins (9.25) only claims
to be based partly on real events. Today's story about Hannah, an atheist
and socialist who becomes involved in the political struggles of the Ashton
spinners, sounds as though it should fit in remarkably well with the beliefs
of the women's movement in the 1990s (well, 1970s and 80s, anyway). QED
focuses on Mike Burrows, inventor of the 'superbike' on which Chris Boardman
won a gold medal at the Barcelona Olympics.(9.30 BBC1).
</TEXT>
