<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / BES sponsors reject attack from Labour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SPONSORS of the Business Expan-sion Scheme defended it yesterday after Mr
Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, called for a 'misuse' of the scheme,
which has already raised Pounds 266m, to be abolished in the Budget. He said
on Monday that a scheme using loans to BES investors turned 'the misery of
the repossessed homeless into a tax-avoidance opportunity'.
Investments in BES companies, which buy property and let it under
assured-tenancy provisions for at least five years, are eligible for income
tax relief at the investor's top marginal rate. Mr Brown complained about a
legislative loophole, first exploited last September, which allows loans to
be made to BES investors using only the value of their BES shares as
security. These loans have made it possible for top-rate taxpayers to pay
only basic rate tax and to leave their investment after six months rather
than the five years originally intended.
Large lenders have avoided bad-debt write-offs by transferring their
repossessed housing stock to BES companies. Lenders which have taken
advantage of the scheme include Barclays Bank, TSB, Bank of Scotland, Bank
of Ireland, Hill Samuel, and Bradford &amp; Bingley, Bristol &amp; West, Britannia,
Leeds Permanent, National &amp; Provincial, and Portman building societies.
A total of Pounds 266m has been raised via loan-backed schemes since they
were introduced last September, and between Pounds 200m and Pounds 250m is
available for investment. The potential cost to the Treasury could exceed
Pounds 200m for this tax year alone.
Mr Ian Pugh, a BES analyst with the Allenbridge Group, one of the two main
intermediaries dealing with BES investors, describes the loan-backed schemes
as 'pure arbitrage'. Shares are sold for Pounds 1 and after six months loans
are offered, typically of 74p or 75p per Pounds 1 invested.
For top-rate taxpayers, who should have received 40p tax relief for each
Pounds 1, this means an annualised return of about 25 per cent.
The loans are repaid by the BES shares once the normal five-year qualifying
period has elapsed. Meanwhile the lenders have received very cheap finance.
The schemes have attracted heavy demand. Mr Charles Fry, chairman of Johnson
Fry, which launched the first non-recourse loan scheme in conjunction with
TSB Mortgage Express, said: 'It's good for people whose houses have been
repossessed because the property is sold for the higher of two independent
valuations.'
He said the schemes were good value for the government compared with the
alternative of direct subsidies. Only Pounds 250m of the Pounds 750m
allocated by the government to housing associations last autumn to buy
housing had been used to buy repossessions, with about 5,000 properties
being bought.
Mr Fry's views were echoed by Mr Tim Villiers, chairman of the BES
Association. 'The figures are straightforward,' he said. 'Ten thousand
properties (Pounds 500m) through BES, with private investors contributing,
costs the government Pounds 200m in tax relief at 40 per cent. Five thousand
houses as a direct grant cost Pounds 250m. Which method is more efficient at
helping to get liquidity, and hence confidence, into the housing market?'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
