<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / Devaluation effect seen in prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANUFACTURERS may be increasing prices in reaction to the higher costs
sparked by sterling's devaluation, government figures indicated yesterday.
They proovided a warning of strong inflationary pressures.
There was a big rise last month in the prices of materials and food
purchased by manufacturers. This was accompanied by indications that
companies were passing on more of these costs to UK customers, possibly in
an effort to rebuild profit margins on hopes of a recovery.
Factory-gate prices last month of manufactured goods excluding food, drink
and tobacco - prices of which fluctuate due to tax changes - rose 2.7 per
cent compared with February last year.
That is the same year-on-year rate as in January and above the 2.4 per cent
year on year increase recorded for each of the last two months of last year.
The prices of materials and fuel purchased by manufacturers rose 0.5 per
cent in February compared with the previous month, the same rise as between
December last year and January. The rises are partly a result of the higher
import prices that resulted from the 15 per cent fall in sterling since last
September, when Britain left the European exchange rate mechanism.
The year-on-year increase in materials and fuel prices last month was 6.9
per cent, unadjusted for seasonal variations. This is up from a revised
increase of 6.3 per cent in the year to January and is the highest
year-on-year rise since May 1989.
The figures from the Central Statistical Office support theories that
inflation, as measured by wholesale prices of factory goods, may start to
climb later this year in response to higher import costs.
More positive news on inflation for many companies is that labour costs are
rising slowly. Many workers have agreed low wage settlements, due partly to
continuing recessionary conditions and fears about unemployment.
Prices at the factory gate of manufactured goods for UK sale, including
food, drink and tobacco, increased by 3.7 per cent in February compared with
the previous February - up from a year-on-year 3.6 per cent in January and
the highest yearly rise since last April.
Between September and February prices paid by manufacturers for materials
and fuel increased by 9.2 per cent. The increases have particularly affected
companies in the metals, food and chemicals businesses which import large
amounts of raw materials.
Allowing for seasonal variations, prices of materials and fuel rose 1.4 per
cent in February compared with January.
</TEXT>
