<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / Fish row protests stepped up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS and ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FISHERMEN IN Grimsby yesterday prevented French fish from being unloaded for
the second day running in the latest stage of a growing European Community
dispute over cheap imports.
Police were investigating a separate incident on Monday night in which
trawlermen at Peterhead, Aberdeenshire, poured diesel oil into the hold of a
Russian factory ship.
The actions in the UK coincided with further protests by French fishermen
against cheap fish imports following a violent clash between fishermen and
riot police outside the fish market in Nantes.
The National Federation of Fishermen's Organisations, representing most
fishermen in England and Wales, said UK fishermen were frustrated by what
they perceived as their disadvantaged financial situation in the face of
government restrictions, a flood of cheap imports from Russia and Norway,
and an increase in fish landed by EC boats.
Mr Barry Deas, federation secretary, said: 'We are operating against weak
demand. What we really need are tight controls on the amount of fish coming
in.'
Mr David Curry, fisheries minister, accused fishermen of simplifying the
problem and warned that protest action would undermine the government's
attempts to argue its case in the EC.
