<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / Vauxhall fights franchise moves
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRICES of new cars in the UK are now lower than in several other European
countries, a report published yesterday by Vauxhall, the UK subsidiary of
General Motors of the US, says.
Vauxhall has issued the study, prepared by management consultants AT
Kearney, in an effort to avoid action by the government to force carmakers
to change some of the controversial terms of their franchise agreements with
dealers.
The motor industry's selective distribution system, which allows carmakers
to sell vehicles through exclusive networks, has been blamed by consumer
groups for making UK car prices higher than in many other parts of Europe.
The investigation of car makers' pricing policies across Europe is set to
intensify in the next two years, as the present 10-year 'block exemption',
which allows car makers to use a selective dealer distribution system in
contravention of European Community competition rules, is due to expire in
mid-1995.
It is understood that carmakers in the UK have rebuffed a request made last
year by the Office of Fair Trading to change some of the more restrictive
terms of their dealer franchise agreements.
The changes were recommended in a report published early last year by the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission after an investigation into UK car prices.
It is understood that the OFT has recommended that the DTI will have to take
action to force implementation of the MMC report's findings.
The MMC report recommended the removal of any restrictions on franchised
dealers which:
Limit the dealers' freedom to advertise outside their territory.
Limit dealers' freedom to hold or acquire dealerships from other car makers
outside their territory.
Prevent dealers holding or acquiring competing dealerships in their
territory (although the supplier may require that any other dealership
acquired be on a distinct and separate site and a reasonable distance away).
Restrict the extent to which dealers can sell car-related goods or services,
such as hire, second-hand car sales, fast-fit or multi-brand servicing
outside their territory.
Limit the number of the manufacturer's cars that any dealer or dealer group
may sell in any given period, or the proportion of the total sales of its
cars that may be made by any dealer or dealer group.
Vauxhall, which ranks second in the UK new-car market, yesterday urged other
carmakers to prepare a new action plan to establish 'common ground' with the
OFT, which could allow changes in franchise agreements that would be
'compatible' with present EC regulations.
</TEXT>
