<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / Fish row protests stepped up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS and ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FISHERMEN IN Grimsby yesterday prevented French fish from being unloaded for
the second day running in the latest stage of a growing European Community
dispute over cheap imports.
Police were yesterday investigating a separate incident on Monday night in
which trawlermen at Peterhead, Aberdeenshire, poured diesel oil into the
hold of a Russian factory ship.
The actions in the UK coincided with further protests by French fishermen
against cheap fish imports following a violent clash between fishermen and
riot police outside the fish market in Nantes.
The National Federation of Fishermen's Organisations, representing most
fishermen in England and Wales, said UK fishermen were frustrated by what
they perceived as their disadvantaged financial situation in the face of
government restrictions, a flood of cheap imports from Russia and Norway,
and an increase in fish landed by EC boats.
Mr Barry Deas, federation secretary, said: 'We are operating against weak
demand. What we really need are tight quantitive controls on the amount of
fish coming in.'
Mr David Curry, fisheries minister, accused fishermen of simplifying the
problem besetting the industry, and inadequately regulating themselves. He
warned that protest action would undermine the government's attempts to
argue its case within the EC.
Mr Curry said: 'It may be that imports are playing some role in the problems
of the market place at the moment. But that is not the only factor. British
fishermen are landing too much fish simultaneously. They are oversupplying
the market.'
The minister described the protest actions in Grimsby and Peterhead as
'totally silly' when UK ministers were urging their French counterparts to
take measures to protect British lorries.
The complex issues besetting the fishing industry were highlighted last
night by Mr Philip Greig, managing director of Abacus Frozen Foods, the
importer of the Russian fish destroyed by Monday night's action in
Peterhead.
Mr Greig said Russian cod was being imported in exchange for locally fished
haddock and whiting. He warned that further protest action would force the
closure of his factory and have a knock-on effect on local fishermen.
Mr Ron Gillan, chief executive of the Scottish North East Fish Producers'
Organisation, said he could not rule out the possibility of protest action
spreading among British ports.
</TEXT>
