<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / Rolls-Royce set to shed 3,000 jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ROLLS-ROYCE, the aero-engine and industrial power group, is likely to shed
between 3,000 and 5,000 jobs this year in the face of continuing recession
in the industry.
The company is expected to announce the cuts tomorrow when it reports its
financial results for last year.
The expected job cuts follow sweeping restructuring during the last two
years which has seen the loss of about 12,000 jobs throughout the group.
Rolls-Royce employed 64,200 people at the end of 1990 - 36,500 in aerospace
 -and about 52,000 at the end of last year, with aerospace accounting for
just under 30,000.
Most of the latest cuts are likely to be concentrated in aerospace, which
accounts for about 60 per cent of the group's Pounds 3.5bn annual turnover.
The company, like its two principal US competitors, General Electric and
Pratt &amp; Whitney, has suffered from the combined effects of the decline in
defence spending and the sharp recession in the civil aviation industry.
Rolls-Royce has faced heavy research and development costs for the Trent,
the engine which will power the new generation of widebodied aircraft.
The job cuts are also part of the company's continuing efforts to improve
efficiency and competitiveness. Rolls-Royce is also continuing to
rationalise its manufacturing, and has announced plans to shut its
helicopter-engine plant at Leavesden, Hertfordshire, and a components
factory at Parkside, Coventry.
Analysts expect Rolls-Royce to report 1992 pre-tax profits of Pounds 50m to
Pounds 90m tomorrow, compared with Pounds 51m in 1991, and to cut its
dividend.
Management, Page 17
</TEXT>
