<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / Lords to rule on card fraud
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE HOUSE of Lords is to be asked to rule on a legal test case over whether
Barclays Bank should have to honour cheques with forged signatures backed by
stolen cheque guarantee cards.
Appeal Court judges said in a 2-1 ruling yesterday that Barclays should be
liable to honour cheques when supported by old bank guarantee cards.
The cards, which are no longer in use, have the terms of the guarantee
printed on them, specifically excluding fraudulent payments.
The judges gave Barclays leave to appeal to the House of Lords after lawyers
for the bank said the ruling could cost it 'several tens of millions of
pounds' if similar cases came to court.
The Master of the Rolls, Sir Thomas Bingham, said he had considerable
hesitation in rejecting the bank's argument that it should not have to
honour such fraudulent payments.
However, he said, the bank's claim about future possible losses might be
exaggerated.
The cards were phased out from January 1990 when Barclays' guarantee came
into line with that offered by other high street banks.
This leaves it to banks' discretion whether to honour such cheques - the
deciding factor being whether the signature is a good enough forgery for
retailers not to be reasonably expected to spot the fraud.
</TEXT>
