<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / Generators told to sell plants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK electricity regulator yesterday suggested to National Power and
PowerGen, the main generators in England and Wales, that they offer for sale
11 power stations that they plan to close either fully or partly later this
month.
Professor Stephen Littlechild, the regulator, said putting them on the
market would provide 'the best safeguard against the possibility or
suspicion of monopoly exploitation.' It would also provide protection
against a big generator closing economic plant with a view to driving up the
price of electricity and, thus, the profitability of other plant.
National Power, the larger of the two companies, strongly rejected Prof
Littlechild's suggestion. It said overcapacity in generation was increasing
and that retaining redundant plant would lead to the closure of more modern
and efficient plant. Electricity production costs would rise and the
environment would suffer.
PowerGen said it did not rule out selling one of its four plants. City
analysts said, however, it was unlikely that either company wanted to sell
their plants.
National Power's robust defence of its actions risks antagonising the
regulator, who has already said he is considering referring the generators
to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission and will decide by 1995.
Analysts believe it unlikely he will make a reference. They think he will
seek a change in their licence which would give him powers to order them to
sell plants.
National Power's stance is a blow to such companies as Cabah Energy, which
wants to buy surplus plant.
Mr Chris Rowland, a director of Cabah Energy, said yesterday his company was
interested in buying plant at five National Power-owned coal-fired stations
with a 1,200MW generating capacity. He said: 'If we acquired all five we
would be using 2.5m tonnes of coal a year.' That constitutes the production
of up to two of the 31 threatened pits.
Prof Littlechild's recommendation followed publication of a report by Touche
Ross, accountants who he had appointed to be inde-pendent assessors on the
closures.
He endorsed their findings that while both companies' decisions to close
plant were reasonable, there were several 'credible organisations'
interested in purchasing stations.
He also said the generators should even consider selling plant they
considered viable. This would provide greater opportunity for
diversification than the present industry structure allowed.
National Power said it would consider on their merit any bids for plant not
scheduled for closure.
The 11 stations scheduled for closure have a total 2,263MW capacity, of
which 1,737MW is from coal-fired plant.
</TEXT>
