<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / South-east in rail cuts frontline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH RAIL'S Network SouthEast commuter operations are to bear the brunt
of service cuts when the new national rail timetable comes into operation in
May, it emerged yesterday.
Mr Brian Wilson, opposition transport spokesman, said the government's plans
for rail privatisation were to blame for the cuts. He said BR was being
forced to create a railway slim enough for the private sector to inherit.
Network SouthEast said its commuter traffic had declined by 7 per cent a
year for the least two years and was expected to go on doing so next year.
Examples of cuts include the loss of six return journeys a day on Sussex
coast services and eight return journeys a day on the south London lines.
There will be peak-hour reductions on the Kent Link, Hastings, Sheerness and
Medway Valley lines.
BR's InterCity division is also making cuts. Hull will lose one of the two
direct trains which link it with London each weekday and the daily return
train between Liverpool and Dover is to be axed. The 15-minute interval
Gatwick Express service will be reduced to 30-minute intervals early in the
morning.
In contrast, Regional Railways, BR's provincial passenger operation, is
increasing services. It will be opening a link to Manchester airport in May
and plans a service between Birmingham Snow Hill and London Marylebone via
Leamington Spa.
British Rail's Trainload Freight division, recently criticised for pricing
freight off the rails, yesterday said it had won a waste-disposal contract
in Manchester that would take 10,000 lorries a year off the roads.
</TEXT>
