<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SUPPORT from opposition parties yesterday enabled the government to fight
off an extensive rebellion from its own backbenchers in the House of Lords
over leasehold reform, Alison Smith writes.
Labour and Liberal Democrat peers joined ministers and Tory loyalists in
voting down amendments which would have restricted the government's plans to
give long leaseholders in blocks of flats the right to club together to buy
the freehold of the property.
A stream of Tory peers, led by Lord Boardman and Lord Peyton - both former
ministers - urged ministers to confine the new rights to leaseholders who
were resident in the flats and who were UK nationals.
Although the rebels attracted the support of Lord Tebbit, a former Tory
party chairman, peers rejected their proposals.
