<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Lib Dems agree to differ on
referendum
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LIBERAL DEMOCRAT MPs are to decide individually whether to support a
referendum on Maastricht when the amendment comes before the Commons. The
arrangement is a tacit admission that they have had to agree to differ.
The acceptance of a free vote on a referendum reflects differences of view
in the party over aspects of their tactics on Maastricht.
There were, for example, various opinions about what line the party should
have taken if, instead of continuing to oppose the Labour amendment which
caused Monday's humiliating government defeat, ministers had said that they
accepted its principle and would alter the bill when it reached the House of
Lords.
Tactics will be discussed again today at the weekly meeting of the 20 MPs.
The party is unmoved by Tory accusations of 'hypocrisy' in its support for
the Labour amendment on Monday, and points out the delays in the bill that
are attributable to the government.
While Mr Paddy Ashdown, the party leader, has called for a referendum on
Maastricht, it was noticeably absent from the party conference motion on
Europe last autumn. Government whips know that Liberal Democrat support is
vital on procedural motions, and have been in constant touch with the party
since January, when the extensive Commons discussions on the legislation
really got under way.
The Liberal Democrats have often voted with the government on motions to
close debate, because they want to make progress with the bill, and to
underline their 'pro-European' credentials. This also underlay their
critical support for the Tories in the 'paving' debate on Maastricht last
autumn, when the government had a majority of just three votes.
Little incentive has been offered to support the Tories on issues of
substance where the government risks defeat. The Liberal Democrat commitment
to proportional representation - to which the government is strongly opposed
 -means that ministers cannot move far enough to satisfy them.
While the party has still to take final decisions on its attitude towards
the amendments on economic and monetary union which could unite Labour and
the Euro-sceptics, it is already so firmly committed to the social chapter
that the government has no real chance of detaching the Liberal Democrat MPs
from its other opponents on these amendments.
</TEXT>
<XX>
