<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: DTI to move part of oil and gas
office to Aberdeen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is to move 60 geologists and engineers with the Department of
Trade and Industry's oil and gas division from London to Aberdeen to set up
an office to deal with North Sea oil development.
Many Scottish businessman and politicians have long been pressing for the
whole of the Petroleum Engineering Directorate to be moved to Aberdeen in
order to strengthen the city as a centre of oil and gas expertise.
Mr Tim Eggar, the energy minister, said that consultants had found 'no clear
case' for doing this.
The new Aberdeen office, he said, would provide services previously
available only in London and would 'take the nationwide lead in the issue of
field development consents'. If, as expected, more oil companies moved from
London to Aberdeen to be near the directorate the office would be expanded
to 80 staff.
A study by accountants Ernst &amp; Young showed, however, that there would be a
loss of business efficiency to the DTI if the whole of the directorate went
to Aberdeen. It acknowledged there would be a 'small gain' in promoting an
agglomeration of industries and skills in Aberdeen, which should improve the
UK international position in offshore supplies and services.
It said the impact of the move on the location of other organisations would
be small and the effect on the costs and efficiency of oil companies would
be neutral. There would be a very small financial cost to the DTI.
Mr Ian Wood, chairman of the Aberdeen-based Wood Group, an offshore service
company, said the decision was a 'step in the right direction'. Mr Wood is a
leading campaigner for moving the whole directorate to Aberdeen.
</TEXT>
<XX>
