<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / World Trade News: Clinton promises aircraft subsidies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton yesterday gave strong support to the US-EC pact
governing Airbus but promised to counter European subsidies with
'significant' government investment in new technology for the next
generation of US aircraft.
Speaking at a news conference with President Francois Mitterrand, he
stressed that 'the (Airbus) agreement must be honoured'. He was echoing his
trade representative, Mr Mickey Kantor, who appeared before the Senate
finance committee yesterday to testify about a range of trade issues.
Under questioning, Mr Kantor rejected a suggestion that the US would bring a
countervailing duty case against the EC. However, he complained about EC
accounting practices. The US had not had access to information on repayment
by Airbus of government loans, he said, adding that if the loans were not
being repaid, the US might withdraw from the pact.
On the subject of Japan, Mr Kantor said the administration was enthusiastic
about a proposal to address the US deficit by negotiating a series of
specific trade targets in order to boost US manufactured exports. Failure to
achieve these 'temporary quantitative indicators' within an agreed time span
would result either in further negotiated measures or US sanctions.
On other subjects he suggested:
The negotiating agenda had been set for the side agreements on labour and
the environment necessary to implement the North American Free Trade
Agreement by January 1, 1994. The entire package might be sent to Congress
by early summer.
Blame for the failure to conclude a Gatt agreement rested on 'the three-year
deadlock between the rest of the world and the EC over agriculture, and
Japan, which took the opportunity of the stalemate to 'avoid contributing
meaningfully' to the talks.
