<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / US and France seek early G7 talks: Western leaders stress
Russia's urgent need for aid
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM and QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENTS Bill Clinton and Francois Mitterrand yesterday called for greater
urgency in helping Russia with western aid.
Both men acknowledged Japan's opposition to the idea of holding an emergency
summit of the Group of Seven leading industrial nations before the regular
summit to be held in Tokyo in July, but said the G7 must move before that.
'I don't believe we can wait until July,' President Clinton said after a
morning meeting with Mr Mitterrand in Washington.
An emergency G7 meeting would probably be useful but might not be possible
in the face of Japan's objections. Nevertheless, the west must move
'aggressively' to help Russia, which might otherwise be forced to look
increasingly to arms sales as the only way of earning hard currency, Mr
Clinton said. Mr Mitterrand, who had advocated an emergency G7 meeting,
added that Japan appeared to misunderstand the urgency of the problems
facing eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union.
White House officials later said a summit of heads of state and government
might not be the only way to address the pressing needs of Russia and the
other former Soviet republics, and suggested a meeting of G7 foreign or
finance ministers might be called.
Chancellor Helmut Kohl has added his voice to the campaign to aid Russia,
according to diplomats, by writing to fellow G7 leaders urging their support
for Mr Yeltsin in his constitutional struggle.
In particular, Mr Kohl has passed on a query from Mr Yeltsin asking for
confirmation of western political support if he is forced to introduce
emergency measures in Russia. The letter reports Mr Yeltsin's confidence
that the Russian military will support him if he seeks emergency powers, the
diplomats said. It also spells out Mr Yeltsin's determination to make one
final effort at reaching agreement with the Russian parliament, while
expressing some doubt about the likelihood of such a deal.
Mr Clinton and Mr Mitterrand agreed on a cautious approach to the idea of
committing more troops to Bosnia. Both said they were willing to increase
their forces only after a peace deal along lines proposed by Mr Cyrus Vance
and Lord Owen had been reached. It was announced in Paris yesterday that Mr
Mitterrand is to host talks tomorrow between the peace negotiators and
President Slobodan Milosevic of Serbia.
Trade issues, which have set France and the US at loggerheads recently, were
reserved for later discussion over lunch, but both presidents struck a
conciliatory note, with Mr Clinton suggesting his recent aggressive comments
about European subsidies to the Airbus consortium might have been
misinterpreted.
Mr Mitterrand said agreement on the Uruguay Round of talks on updating the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade was important, but could not be
achieved by piecemeal negotiations.
Air subsidies, Page 6
</TEXT>
