<HEADLINE>
FT  10 MAR 93 / Gold seized from offices of Kanemaru
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES LEADBEATER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A TEAM of investigators yesterday seized 100kg of gold bars from the Tokyo
office of Mr Shin Kanemaru, until last year a powerful figure in the Liberal
Democratic party (LDP) and the godfather of Japanese politics.
The Tokyo prosecutors' office, which is investigating Mr Kanemaru's alleged
tax evasion, found gold bars worth about Y1bn (Pounds 5.84m) in the office
in Nagatcho, close to the parliament in central Tokyo.
As gold can be purchased anonymously, it is alleged that Mr Kanemaru
accumulated his holdings to avoid paying income tax. Mr Kanemaru faces
allegations that he used some of the political funds he collected for his
personal purposes. He and his private secretary were arrested on Saturday
over alleged tax evasion between 1987 and 1989 which could amount to more
than Y400m.
Mr Kanemaru resigned from parliament in October after being fined Y200,000
following his admission that he received an illegal political donation of
Y500m from Tokyo Sagawa Kyubin, a scandal-tainted trucking company.
During the late 1980s Mr Kanemaru established his position as the most
powerful figure within the then Takeshita faction, which dominated the
ruling LDP, through his legendary ability to raise money.
Estimates of Mr Kanemaru's liquid assets, largely held in forms which do not
need to be registered with the authorities, vary.
However it is estimated that in addition to the Y1bn in gold bars, he also
held between Y2.8bn and Y5bn in discount bank bonds. NHK, the broadcasting
corporation, reported that Mr Kanemaru's hidden assets are thought to be
worth Y7bn.
Discount bonds, which Mr Kanemaru began to buy in 1984, can be purchased
anonymously. Opposition party leaders alleged that Mr Kanemaru's decision to
keep such large sums in unregistered bonds and gold bars was evidence that
he was trying to avoid paying tax.
Investigators disclosed that in the days before his arrest Mr Kanemaru's
aides, aware that an investigation was under way, moved large quantities of
bonds, gold and cash between Mr Kanemaru's house, offices and other
locations.
Mr Kanemaru and his secretary are due to be charged by March 13 and could
remain in custody at the Tokyo detention centre until March 17.
</TEXT>
