<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 93 / International Company News: Marriott set to sign deal with
bondholders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MARRIOTT Corporation, the US hotel and food services group, said yesterday
it was poised to sign an agreement with disgruntled bondholders.
Bondholders have been protesting at the company's plans to spin off its
hotel management operations into a separately-quoted entity, Marriott
International. One of the protesting groups is led by Chicago-based PPM
America, part of the Prudential insurance company of the UK.
It was unclear yesterday whether the agreement would resolve the dispute.
Marriott declined to say what the terms would be, but they are thought to
centre on improvements to the capital structure of the remaining Marriott
group, which will house the group's property assets and airport-tollroad
concessions.
Under the demerger plan, this company, which would be quoted, would be
renamed Host Marriott.
During the past few months, bondholders have split into two camps. One is a
group of large US institutions, thought to include The California Public
Employees Retirement System (Calpers) and the Teachers Insurance and Annuity
Association and represented by Goldman Sachs. The company's negotiations
have been with this group.
A second group is led by PPM America. These bondholders, who purchased new
Marriott debt securities last year, have already filed one lawsuit against
the company, and are threatening to expand the litigation.
Yesterday, Mr John Stark, general counsel for PPM America, said the
'litigating' bondholders were not 'specifically aware' of the proposed
settlement terms.
However, his general understanding was that the deal would not meet their
demands that credit quality and trading value of the bonds be fully
restored. If this was the case, he said, litigation would still be pursued.
Under the original 'demerger' plan, Host Marriott would have retained
virtually all Marriott Corporation's Dollars 3bn of long-term debt.
By separating out the financially healthy hotel management business, the
company hoped to accelerate its expansion, allowing it to take advantage of
an upturn in the economy unimpeded by the group's heavy debt burden.
Although Marriott shares rose on news of this scheme, bond prices dropped
sharply. Moody's, the Wall Street rating agency, downgraded Marriott bonds
from investment to non-investment grade.
The original scheme suggested Marriott International would provide a Dollars
600m credit facility to Host Marriott. During the lengthy negotiations with
the Goldman Sachs bondholders, there had been talk of expanding this,
perhaps to Dollars 900m. However, sources suggested yesterday the deal would
combine an enhanced credit facility with a reshuffling of some debt to
Marriott International.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Marriott Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
