<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 93 / Leyland Daf failed to file accounts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE 1991 accounts of Leyland Daf, the failed van and truckmaker, have not
been filed at Companies House and are now more than four months overdue, the
government said yesterday, David Owen writes.
Mr Neil Hamilton, a junior trade and industry minister, said the accounts
were due by the end of last October and that default procedures had been
initiated last year.
In a written answer to a question from Mr Austin Mitchell, Labour MP for
Great Grimsby, Mr Hamilton said that follow-up letters were issued on
November 16 and January 8.
The government had decided that further action against the directors would
be inappropriate as responsibility for the company's affairs now lay with
the administrative receiver appointed last month.
Meanwhile Leyland Daf dealers yesterday attacked a Pounds 250,000
advertising campaign that criticises the government's handling of the
company's financial crisis.
Posters and press advertisements calling for support in saving jobs at the
company have slogans including 'The government's too mean to buy a bunch of
Dafs'.
The dealers said the campaign - paid for by Leyland Daf Finance, one of the
operations to escape receivership - is 'misplaced and untimely' with
management buy-outs planned at the Birmingham and Leyland plants.
</TEXT>
