FT  09 MAR 93 / Clinton agrees extra cut in spending proposals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton yesterday agreed to cut an additional Dollars 55bn
(Pounds 38.7bn) from his spending proposals after meeting budget experts
from the House of Representatives, the White House said, Reuter reports from
Washington.
During the meeting with members of the House budget committee at the White
House, Mr Clinton 'agreed to accept Dollars 55bn in additional cuts over
five years', said White House press secretary Dee Dee Myers.
She said the exact programmes that would be reduced were not yet determined.
The deeper reductions were necessary because of revised figures by the
Congressional Budget Office which showed that under Mr Clinton's proposals
his plan to reduce the deficit by Dollars 140bn would fall short of the
goal.
