FT  09 MAR 93 / International Company News: Canadian Pacific arm in CDollars
160m equity issue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CANADIAN PACIFIC's Forest Products arm, CPFP, is planning to raise CDollars
160m (USDollars 128m) of new equity in order to bolster working capital and
to support the remaining portion of its heavy investment programme.
However, Canadian Pacific is not taking up any of the 8m common shares,
which are being sold at CDollars 20 a share to an investment group headed by
Scotia McLeod. Its total interest in CPFP will drop from 70 per cent to 60.7
per cent.
The Forest Products arm raised USDollars 75m in a debenture issue in January
and last raised new equity in 1992 with an issue at CDollars 26.50 a share.
CP took up 20 per cent.
CPFP, one of North America's biggest newsprint producers, has omitted its
common share dividend to conserve cash. It suffered a loss for 1992 of
CDollars 248m, or CDollars 4.82 a share, on sales of Dollars 1.8bn, after
restructuring charges.
SNC, Canada's biggest engineering group, benefited from rationalisation and
growing international business, which are helping to offset the long
domestic recession. Fourth-quarter net profit was CDollars 6.5m, or 45 cents
a share, against a loss of CDollars 1.9m, or 17 cents, a year earlier on
revenues ahead at CDollars 255m, against CDollars 211m.
