<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 93 / UK Company News: Domestic &amp; General rides the recession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SLUGGISH SALES on the high street failed to restrict growth at Domestic &amp;
General.
The USM-traded specialist domestic appliance breakdown insurer yesterday
reported a 26 per cent increase in pre-tax profits to Pounds 3.43m (Pounds
2.73m) for the six months to end-December.
D&amp;G, in which Eagle Star, the composite insurer, has a 10 per cent stake,
lifted the interim dividend by 25 per cent to 7.5p. Earnings per share were
also ahead 26 per cent, to 33.55p.
Mr Howard James, managing director, said that the group intended to continue
its expansion in the UK, where it has established marketing agreements with
leading manufacturers such as Zanussi, Grundig and Electrolux and retailers
such as Selfridges and Comet to sell its policies.
He said that most of the group's recent growth reflected an increase in the
overall size of the market for domestic appliance insurance.
Even so D&amp;G is beginning to target markets in Europe. It is authorised to
underwrite in France and has recently reached agreement with Plus Ultra, a
subsidiary of Norwich Union, to sell policies in Spain.
Gross premiums increased 23 per cent to Pounds 26.2m (Pounds 21.4m). Other
income was up 22 per cent to Pounds 265,000 (Pounds 217,000).
Underwriting profits amounted to Pounds 6.14m (Pounds 5.13m). Expenses rose
to Pounds 5.55m (Pounds 5.22m). Net investment income was up 8.9 per cent to
Pounds 2.86m (Pounds 2.63m), despite lower interest rates.
</TEXT>
