<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 93 / British talks with PLO prompt Israeli protest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS, Middle East Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ISRAEL last night summoned the British ambassador to protest at the UK's
decision to resume top-level contacts with the Palestine Liberation
Organisation which were broken off following Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in
1990.
Mr Yossi Beilin, the deputy foreign minister, said that the action 'might
harm the chances to resume the peace process' in the Middle East. An Israeli
foreign ministry statement described the move as 'a prize for the
Palestinians who have yet to announce their readiness to return to the
process'.
British officials were dismayed at the reaction and stressed that the
decision was taken solely to assist the peace process.
The break in relations between the PLO and Britain was in protest at the
organisation's support for Iraq's President Saddam Hussein. Britain has
hinted for some time that the ban on top-level contacts was under review.
Mr Douglas Hogg, a minister of the Foreign Office, will today meet Mr Faisal
Husseini, the leading Palestinian in the Arab territories occupied by
Israel; Mr Afif Safieh, head of the PLO delegation in London, and an
official from PLO headquarters in Tunis. On Thursday Mr Hogg will meet Mr
Beilin.
The Foreign Office said: 'The peace process is at a delicate stage. We are
urging all sides to agree to an early resumption of negotiations. The PLO
will have an influence on important decisions.'
The PLO has warned that it cannot resume peace negotiations with Israel
until substantial progress has been made towards resolving the crisis over
the 396 Palestinians deported by Israel to southern Lebanon in December.
A visit last month to the region by Mr Warren Christopher, the US secretary
of state, failed to overcome the obstacle but he is expected soon to issue
formal invitations for a resumption of negotiations in Washington during the
second half of April. Syria, Lebanon and Jordan have all expressed their
willingness to attend.
</TEXT>
