FT  09 MAR 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBC2's generally excellent foreign affairs series Assignment (7.45) asks
whether colonialism is coming back into fashion, what with American marines
in Somalia and the World Bank dictating terms in so many places. BBC1 shows
the first episode of Luv by Carla Lane. They are still describing her work
as 'family comedy' though ever since 'Butterflies' it has been moving closer
to tragedy. It would be more honest to take off the laughter track and
present it for what it is. This series is about a self-made man, played by
Michael Angelis, who 'gives his wife and three adopted children everything
money can buy, but doesn't realise money can't buy them what they really
need' (8.00). ITV screens its pilot for a British version of 'The Golden
Girls', Brighton Belles, within its 'Comedy Playhouse' season. Sheila
Hancock, Sheila Gish and Wendy Craig play the younger trio and Jean Boht
takes the mother role played by Estelle Getty in the US original (8.30).
Channel 4's Without Walls examines the lives of early actresses who were
assumed to be prostitutes; and invites George Melly to have a go at the
later work of Henry Moore (9.00).
