<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: The story of three men in a vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCARCELY HAD the echo died from a chorus of ministers calling at the weekend
for loyalty in Tory ranks yesterday than the divisions, and plotting,
re-opened over Maastricht.
Conservative MPs divide into three broad camps: the die-hard Euro-rebels to
whom defeating Maastricht is top priority and who want to exploit every
chance to de-rail the bill; the government loyalists who want Maastricht
approved and are prepared to fight for it; and the frustrated MPs in the
middle - who want most to turn parliament's attention to other business.
THE DIE-HARD: MR Michael Spicer, MP for Worcestershire South, voted against
the government last night. The unofficial whip for Tory Euro-sceptics was
far from repentant yesterday - in spite of the appeals for party unity, from
the prime minister downwards, ringing in his ears.
'Some of the speeches have actually exacerbated the matters,' he said. 'The
attempt to denigrate, to belittle and in some cases to even misinterpret
what is a very sincerely held belief - and also highly representative of
public opinion - is in itself damaging to party unity.'
He will not identify individuals but it is clear that personal antagonism
remains. 'Certainly there are ministers and party functionaries who are
going beyond what is sensible in terms of the rhetoric they are using - it
is counter-productive.'
The Euro-sceptics still be-lieve opposition to Maastricht is increasing, in
spite of signs of frustration in their ranks.
There is a defensiveness, however. Mr Spicer, a former minister, voted for
the 1986 Single European Act, which increased the powers of Brussels. In
retrospect he would want changes to that legislation. But, he says: 'There
is a very great distinction between a treaty and piece of legislation which
aims at trying to strengthen a common market - the single European act - and
one which overtly sets out to set up a united states of Europe.'
THE LOYALIST: Mr Ian Taylor, MP for Esher, voted with the government last
night. A leading member of the 'positive Europeans' group of Tory MPs, he
blends strong support for the treaty with frustration at the activities of
Euro-sceptics in his party.
'I think their collective behaviour is absurd. The only beneficiaries are
the Labour party and the Liberals, and the damage inflicted to the
government and the chances of economic recovery are very considerable,' he
said yesterday.
'The case can be made for its being honourable to oppose the government on a
point of principle, but to attempt to undermine the government on a point of
procedure, when the effect is to delay other measures the government wants
to bring forward and to give satisfaction to Labour, is inept.'
The commitment to the treaty from government and from business leads him to
emphasise how vital ratification is. He has not only voted for the
government throughout, but has occasionally intervened in the extended
debates to make the pro-Maastricht argument and contrast Labour's readiness
to prolong discussion with its professed support for the treaty.
So far, he says, the government has handled the bill 'fairly well', but he
believes that the time has come to force the pace of parliamentary
discussion.
THE SIMPLY FED-UP: Mr Michael Clark, MP for Rochford, also voted with the
government. He opposes the Maastricht treaty but by yesterday, his
exasperation at the hours devoted to its ratification were surfacing
publicly.
'The government will win slowly and if the government is going to win, well,
let's for God's sake get this thing out of the way as quickly as possible,'
he said.
So he would not vote to stop the government getting its business - and would
not back an amendment like Labour's last night on the Committee of the
Regions, because of the extra delay it would cause.
Yet his sympathy for Euro-sceptic colleagues is still strong. 'They have
been consistent and they have been honourable and they believe strongly what
they are doing. I don't have any derogatory thoughts about them at all.'
Appeals to loyalty may have had an impact, Mr Clark hinted - but he denied
that lay behind his latest decisions.
'The prime minster has a right to a certain amount of loyalty from people
who stood on the Conservative ticket at the last election. It doesn't please
me at all not to have given him support these last two or three months. The
government has a right to get its business.'
He promised: 'I'm not sniping on the sidelines, I wont take part in
guerrilla tactics.'
Mr Clark, who has backed the principle of greater free trade in Europe,
listed all the other problems still facing the government - the recession,
privatisation of British Rail, British Coal and Post Office to name but
some.
'All this is being pushed back and it is being pushed further and further.
This time next year we will be half way through this parliament and all we
will have done is Maastricht, Maastricht, Maastricht.'
</TEXT>
