FT  09 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Position on EC seats still unclear
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT last night declined to clear up confusion over how the six
new British seats to the European parliament are to be allocated, saying
only that it expected to come to a view 'at a very early date,' David Owen
writes.
Mr Tristan Garel-Jones, the foreign office minister, acknowledged the matter
was 'extremely urgent' but said the government was still considering how
best to proceed.
Mr George Robertson, shadow foreign office minister, said such an answer was
not good enough with the next European elections only 56 weeks away. The
response was another example of the 'dazed confusion' the government was in
over Europe, he added.
It was decided at last year's European summit in Edinburgh to give Britain
six more MEPs, bringing the total to 87. In December prime minister John
Major indicated Britain would retain the 'first past the post system' for
the 1994 European elections.
