<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: Brown attacks BES 'misuse'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN and JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR YESTERDAY called for immediate action to end 'misuse' of business
expansion schemes as it stepped up its attacks on the government for not
standing up to the banks and big business.
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, targeted BES-linked schemes which he
said could cost the Treasury Pounds 400m and was making 'the misery of the
repossessed homeless into a tax-avoidance opportunity for top-rate taxpayers
and the banking establishment'.
Claiming that BES companies launched in the last 10 days alone would cost
the Treasury Pounds 160m, Mr Brown promised that Labour would try to put a
stop to them by tabling amendments to the post-Budget Finance Bill if the
government did not act.
Mr Brown said the failure of Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, to take
action against lending institutions - typically banks and building societies
 -was either 'incompetence or a failure to stand up to the vested interests
close to the Conservative party'.
Under the business expansion scheme lending institutions with repossessed
properties on their books are able to transfer the property to a BES
company, which then rents it out for five years before selling it back to
the original lender.
Investors buy shares in the BES company, receiving tax relief of 40p in the
pound if they pay income tax at the top rate, making an effective net
investment of 60p.
Six months later the institution makes loans of typically 74p for each pound
invested. Shares in the BES company are the only security for the loan and
there is no recourse to the investor's other assets.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
