<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 93 / Parliament and Politics: PM ponders wounding Maastricht
defeat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT'S opponents have drawn blood. Last night Mr John Major's
government suffered its first defeat on the Maastricht treaty. It was also,
incidentally, the first parliamentary defeat since Mr Major walked into
Downing Street in November 1990. It was humiliating for the prime minister.
It was not fatal - for the treaty or for the government.
The passage by the combined forces of the opposition parties and Tory
Euro-sceptics of an obscure and, of itself, relatively unimportant amendment
to the Maastricht legislation has two effects.
The first is to deliver yet another blow to a weak and uncertain government.
The ecstatic reaction of the Tory rebels in the Commons chamber when the
vote was announced underlined again that Mr Major cannot command his own
party. He has a paper majority of 20. But 26 Tories voted against him and
nearly 20 abstained.
Just two days earlier he had made a strong and deliberately public plea for
the unity he needs to restore his authority. His most senior ministers had
warned that the government's entire programme - from action to tackle crime
to further reforms of the education system - was being jeopardised by the
parliamentary logjam over Maastricht.
The diehard opponents of further European integration on the Tory
backbenches rewarded their leader with an equally public slap in the face.
Labour and the Liberal Democrats, though both committed to the eventual
ratification of the treaty, decided that they could not pass up the chance
of delivering another kick to the government.
The second effect of the defeat is to prolong still further the debate on
ratification in the House of Commons. Under the arcane procedures of
Westminster another chunk of parliamentary time must now be added to the
debate among MPs. This report stage will follow the detailed line-by-line
examination of the legislation in its present committee stage.
The actual substance of the amendment is hardly relevant. It is designed to
ensure that British representatives on the EC's new Committee of the Regions
will be chosen from elected local councillors. The government had wanted
them to be appointees, but was ready to concede if it had thought the main
opposition parties would back down.
So the corrosive debate will now continue until well into the summer - and
perhaps beyond. Only the hardest of the hardline opponents of the treaty
believe that it will in the end fall. Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, and
Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, are both publicly pledged to
its passage.
If the two opposition leaders attempted to renege on that commitment they
would split their own parties. Many Liberal Democrats feel deeply uneasy
about Mr Ashdown calling one day for the government to speed up ratification
and the next voting to delay it. There are 100 Labour MPs who would defy
their leaders if they judged they were being asked to wreck the treaty.
But Mr Major knows now that the speed of the legislation cannot be dictated
by the government. He is totally reliant on the goodwill of the opposition -
particularly the Liberal Democrats - to secure his timetable for
ratification. Neither Mr Smith nor Mr Ashdown will make life easy.
Before last night's vote, MPs had already spent about 100 hours debating the
legislation. It will need the same again to complete the committee stage.
The new report stage could take another two or three weeks.
Then the bill has to go to the House of Lords. The government's business
managers will have to dump still more of its domestic legislation if the
process is to be completed by July or August. The agony might be prolonged
until October. There may be yet further defeats. The opposition parties are
committed to the inclusion of the social chapter. Some of the Tory
Euro-sceptics now seem so detached from their own party that they may do
anything to wreck the treaty. They will be bought off only by the referendum
Mr Major has consistently rejected.
As he contemplates defeat this morning, the prime minister will draw comfort
from the fact that in the end the large pro-European majority at Westminster
will give him his legislation. But who now could refer to Maastricht as
'game, set and match'.
</TEXT>
