<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 93 / Film production gains from a weak pound
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE ARE growing signs of life in the British film production industry,
largely because of the weakness of the pound against the dollar.
Mr Sydney Samuelson, the British film commissioner, just back from meeting
senior executives of all the main studios in Los Angeles, found evidence of
renewed interest.
'There was 10 times the level of interest this time compared with a year
ago,' said Mr Samuelson, who heads the National Film Commission, a body
funded by the government.
The commission took front-page advertisements in the Hollywood trade press,
highlighting the way in which British costs have come down because of the
pound's fall.
Mr Samuelson provided real examples such as a two-person sound crew for 60
hours, or six days, shooting in the Highlands of Scotland which cost a total
of Dollars 2,700 on September 2 last year but by February 15 would only have
cost Dollars 1,917. The savings hold true for every category from
non-speaking extras to make-up artists.
When Mr Samuelson went for meetings with studio executives the
advertisements were often on their desks.
'They like working with British technicians and they like shooting in the
UK. But when it's too expensive they are prepared to compromise and go
somewhere else,' said Mr Samuelson, who believes the government is now more
sympathetic to the industry.
Last year 48 feature films went before the cameras in the UK - three less
than in 1991. Mr Samuelson is more optimistic for this year.
The film commission hopes, for example, that a film about King Arthur and
the Round Table will start shooting at Pinewood studios in June and that
part of a new film based on The Three Musketeers will be based in the UK.
A Dollars 40m-a-year NBC television series, Jewels, set in the UK, will be
filmed in the Irish republic because of better incentives.
The UK film industry hopes that more encouragement from the government may
be on the way, either in next week's or the autumn Budget.
</TEXT>
