<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 93 / Trident costs disputed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE MINISTRY of Defence will come under pressure this week to clarify its
arrangements for obtaining Trident strategic missiles from the US, following
a report that US defence cuts could raise the cost of the programme to
Britain by more than Pounds 200m.
The report by the British American Security Information Council, an
independent lobby group, says reduced production plans by the US navy would
increase the unit cost of missiles by Dollars 13m to Dollars 49m (Pounds
34m).
Britain has already paid for many of the missiles it requires to equip four
submarines - thought to be about 70. The missiles will be drawn from a
shared pool and serviced in the US.
The report says a conservative estimate of the extra cost of missiles
remaining to be paid for by the UK is between Dollars 221m and Dollars 312m.
The Ministry of Defence yesterday rejected this figure as 'completely
unrealistic'. It did not yet have conclusive information about the impact of
the US changes on Britain's costs but said the increase would not be
significant 'and could be nothing'.
Mr David Clark, Labour party defence spokesman, said he was 'alarmed' by the
report.
The all-party Commons defence committee is due to question officials about
the progress of the Trident nuclear deterrent programme tomorrow. Last year
it estimated the Trident missile cost - not counting warheads, which will be
British-made - at Pounds 988m. The report says the US is thought to have
covered at least 20 per cent of the UK's share of the costs until now.
</TEXT>
