<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 93 / Engineering halts decline in orders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL CHEESERIGHT, Midlands Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ORDER BOOKS of engineering companies in the West Midlands, the traditional
heart of the industry, have stopped shrinking over the past three months
and, for the first time since last May, the proportion of companies
reporting increased demand is higher than those reporting lower demand.
The latest survey of business trends, covering 470 companies, carried out by
the Engineering Employers' Federation West Midlands and published yesterday,
showed that in February 36 per cent of companies experienced an improvement
in the level of domestic orders and 49 per cent an improvement in export
orders.
With 45 per cent of companies expecting total orders to increase over the
next three months, Mr David Botterill, the chief executive of EEF West
Midlands, said there were 'emerging signs of recovery'.
Although 40 per cent of companies are expecting higher utilisation of their
capacity over the next quarter, there is little sign of higher capital
spending and the employment prospects remain bleak.
Only 14 per cent of companies expect to take on more people, although Mr
Botterill expected a slowdown in the rate of job losses.
Such a slowdown has already started. Birmingham City Council recently noted
that although unemployment totals in the city had risen for 31 successive
months, 'the increase has fallen from an average of 17,500 in the year to
January 1992 to 6,000 in the year to January 1993'.
</TEXT>
