<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 93 / Solicitors to sue Mackay over fees
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LAW Society, the solicitors' governing body, is to sue Lord Mackay, the
lord chancellor, over his plans to introduce standard fees for criminal
legal aid work in the magistrates' courts.
This is the second time the profession has taken a lord chancellor to court
over legal aid. In 1986 the Bar and the Law Society sought a judicial review
of a refusal by Lord Hailsham, then lord chancellor, to award legal aid
lawyers a 'fair and reasonable' pay rise. The case was settled out of court.
The decision to seek a judicial review of Lord Mackay's standard fee
proposals follows a year-long campaign by solicitors to persuade Lord Mackay
not to replace the current system of paying solicitors on the basis of the
work actually done with a system based on standard fees for different
categories of case.
Lord Mackay intends to introduce the standard fees system from April 1. The
society argues that standard fees will overpay some lawyers and underpay
others. This could result in mistrust between client and solicitor and
reduce the quality of the service available to those who need legal aid.
Mr Mark Sheldon, president of the Law Society, said: 'This case is about
ensuring that proper representation remains available to to those who need
criminal legal aid. This is not a dispute in which we are seeking more pay
for solicitors.'
The society said it hoped its application for judicial review could be dealt
with quickly and it urged Lord Mackay not to make the regulations to
introduce the system until the matter had been resolved.
</TEXT>
