<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 93 / 250,000 jobless 'are black or Asian'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR and DAVID GOODHART
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEARLY 250,000 of Britain's unemployed are black or Asian, according to
figures released yesterday by the GMB, the general union. It said blacks and
Asians are more than twice as likely to be unemployed as white people. One
in four black workers have no job and just under one in every five Asians
are unemployed.
Based on figures from the April 1991 census and updated to take into account
the rise in unemployment over the past 23 months, the survey said the worst
area for Asian unemployment is the east London borough of Tower Hamlets,
with as many as 45 per cent jobless.
Liverpool has the highest proportion of black people without work, amounting
to 38 per cent of the black labour force in the city.
At its first national race conference yesterday, the GMB called on the Home
Office not to go ahead with cutting grant funding to local authorities to
help ethnic minority pro-jects.
Meanwhile, a radical dilution of the definition of 'full employment' to mean
that nobody should be unemployed for more than one year has been suggested
by the influential Employment Policy Institute.
The Institute, usually regarded as left-of-centre, yesterday launched a
'full employment year' designed to foster a wide-ranging national debate on
how to solve mass unemployment.
But Professor Richard Layard, one of Britain's best known experts on
unemployment and a leading member of the institute, stressed that a new
definition of full employment was required concentrating on combat-ing
long-term unemployment.
On present figures that could mean a state of 'full employment' with 2m
people unemployed for periods of up to 12 months. He said: 'Some short-term
unemployment is necessary to control inflation'.
He also stressed the cost of unemployment to those in jobs and estimated
that every tax-payer is now paying an average of Pounds 1,000 a year. Prof
Layard has stressed that the cost of benefit and lost taxes through
unemployment is Pounds 30bn a year. Those out of work for more than one year
alone cost Pounds 8bn.
Many unemployed executives and other professionals will not find
conventional jobs again and should be encouraged to become 'self-employed
portfolio workers' with two or three part-time jobs, according to Full
Employment UK.
The lobby group says that in spite of the recent reductions in
self-employment it remains a vital source of future employment and should be
promoted in next week's Budget through training credits of Pounds 250 to
help portfolio workers get established. Full Employment UK says that 200,000
people could be helped in this way at a cost of Pounds 50m.
</TEXT>
