<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 93 / World Trade News: France warned on oilseeds deal - Paris
playing into hands of Americans, Commission claims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FRANCE told its Community partners again yesterday that it could not accept
any world trade reform package containing the oilseeds agreement reached
last November with the US.
But it was warned by the European Commission that it was playing into the
hands of the Americans, who would welcome the chance to win a better deal
for US farmers.
The exchange came as Mr Jacques Delors, Commission president, suggested
informally to EC foreign ministers that a Uruguay Round accord should
incorporate 'social parameters' offering an agreed minimum of rights to
workers.
The implication was that Europe was being unfairly undercut by sweatshop
labour in Asia.
Mr Delors was following up remarks he made in a speech in Paris on Friday.
But his spokesman insisted he was expressing well-known views, and not
trying to delay a conclusion to the Round.
Sir Leon Brittan, trade commissioner, reporting earlier to the foreign
ministers on talks in Washington with Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade
representative, said he believed the US wanted to finish the Round this
year, and did not want new subjects on the agenda.
Mr Roland Dumas, French foreign minister, told his colleagues that France
had been 'totally consistent'. The Commission still had to prove that the
Uruguay Round farm chapter, and the oilseeds deal, were compatible with last
year's reform of the Common Agricultural Policy.
The Uruguay Round 'final act' - the foundation of attempts to conclude more
than six years of world trade reform talks - was a reasonable basis for
negotiations, Mr Dumas conceded, 'except on agriculture'.
France 'will not accept a global agreement which includes oilseeds in its
present form,' he added.
Mr Rene Steichen, EC agriculture commissioner, insisted last November's
agreement was 'in line with the CAP', and that 'it remains the basis for an
agreement. . . fresh negotiations on agriculture would only please the US'.
The French government, which faces a crushing defeat in parliamentary
elections later this month, threatened to veto the oilseeds agreement if it
were put to a vote yesterday. Both the Commission and the current Danish
presidency of the EC decided not to bring matters to a head, even though Mr
Steichen fears an advantageous deal for the EC could unravel if not quickly
confirmed.
According to Mr Steichen, a vote is now likely when foreign ministers meet
in Luxembourg on April 5.
It is unclear whether the likely new right-wing coalition in France will be
more malleable on the Washington agreement. But senior EC officials do not
rule out the possibility that France will simply be outvoted.
The 'veto' it threatens is based on the so-called Luxembourg compromise, a
1966 political agreement allowing an EC member to invoke 'very important'
national interests to block a deal.
But the device is all but defunct. 'It has never been tested on an external
issue,' one senior diplomat says. It has not been used since the Single
European Act came into force in 1987, and attempts at Luxembourg compromise
'vetoes' by Germany and the UK not long before that both failed.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
    QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
    USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
