<HEADLINE>
FT  09 MAR 93 / IMF approves credit for Poland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE IMF has approved a Dollars 655m (Pounds 461m) stand-by credit to Poland
partly aimed at reducing the country's Dollars 46bn debt, George Graham
reports from Washington. The Fund suspended an earlier arrangement with
Poland in 1991 as the country failed to meet targets for curbing inflation
and cutting the budget deficit.
The Polish parliament last month approved a tight budget aimed at lopping
the deficit to 81,000bn zlotys (Pounds 3.4bn) or 5 per cent of GDP, opening
the way for the IMF to give its approval to a new economic plan. The IMF
said yesterday the Polish authorities had asked for a quarter of each
disbursement from the stand-by credit to be set aside for debt reduction,
and said it would be prepared to increase the credit if a debt reduction
agreement could be reached with commercial bank creditors.
</TEXT>
